1
00:00:00,240 --> 00:00:04,760
Big trading educators make fair 
value gaps sound mysterious! 

2
00:00:04,760 --> 00:00:09,760
Truth is, they're just showing where 
buyers and sellers couldn't agree! 

3
00:00:09,760 --> 00:00:14,000
They're just fancy words for 
supply and demand imbalances! 

4
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:17,520
So today I'll strip away the complexity, and show  

5
00:00:17,520 --> 00:00:21,480
you how to spot and trade them, easily!
 
Chapter 1: Introduction to Fair Value Gaps

6
00:00:21,480 --> 00:00:27,080
Fair value gaps show up when price 
moves fast, skipping over some levels. 

7
00:00:27,080 --> 00:00:31,120
These gaps happen when buyers 
and sellers aren't balanced. 

8
00:00:31,120 --> 00:00:34,120
And traders pay attention to these gaps because  

9
00:00:34,120 --> 00:00:38,400
they can show where price might 
turn around or keep going. 
  

10
00:00:38,400 --> 00:00:45,040
A fair value gap is a place where price 
moved so fast, it left a blank space. 

11
00:00:45,040 --> 00:00:49,720
On smaller time frames, you can 
see no trading happened there. 

12
00:00:49,720 --> 00:00:54,680
It's like a vacuum in the market.
But these gaps are important because  

13
00:00:54,680 --> 00:00:59,920
they often act like magnets for price. 
 
And the market likes to fill these gaps. 

14
00:01:00,600 --> 00:01:07,160
This means price often comes back to these levels.
They are important because fair value gaps can  

15
00:01:07,160 --> 00:01:12,160
help you predict where price might go.
And they can also help you find good  

16
00:01:12,160 --> 00:01:15,720
places to enter or exit trades. 
 
 
Chapter 2: The Theory Behind Fair Value Gaps

17
00:01:15,720 --> 00:01:22,080
Markets are always trying to find the right 
price for things. This is called price discovery. 

18
00:01:22,080 --> 00:01:26,320
It happens when buyers and 
sellers agree on a price. 

19
00:01:26,320 --> 00:01:34,560
But sometimes, the market moves so fast that it 
skips over some prices. This is how gaps form.
  

20
00:01:34,560 --> 00:01:39,680
Fair value gaps show up when there's 
not enough trading at certain prices. 

21
00:01:39,680 --> 00:01:46,480
It's like a jump in the market. These gaps 
often happen when big players make large orders. 

22
00:01:46,480 --> 00:01:50,360
They can take all the available 
trades, leaving a gap.
  

23
00:01:50,360 --> 00:01:57,320
The market wasn't balanced. On one side, there 
were more buyers or sellers than on the other. 

24
00:01:57,320 --> 00:02:02,760
And this imbalance can give us clues 
about where the market might go next. 

25
00:02:02,760 --> 00:02:08,760
Fair value gaps often act like magnets. 
And the market likes to fill these gaps. 

26
00:02:08,760 --> 00:02:13,760
It's like the market wants to go back 
and check if the price is right. 
  

27
00:02:13,760 --> 00:02:17,080
Now, there are different types 
of gaps. Some happen when the  

28
00:02:17,080 --> 00:02:20,840
market opens higher or lower than it closed. 

29
00:02:20,840 --> 00:02:25,080
Others, like fair value 
gaps, happen during trading. 

30
00:02:25,080 --> 00:02:31,120
They all show times when the market moved 
fast and left some prices untested.
  

31
00:02:31,120 --> 00:02:34,760
Fair value gaps will help you 
see the market's "memory". 

32
00:02:34,760 --> 00:02:38,520
It remembers these gaps and 
often comes back to them. 

33
00:02:38,520 --> 00:02:46,200
This can help you predict where price might go 
or find good places to enter or exit trades.
  

34
00:02:46,200 --> 00:02:51,400
Now, let’s address the elephant in the room. 
There are hundreds of fair value gaps every  

35
00:02:51,400 --> 00:02:57,120
day, on all time frame. If you trade every gap 
you see, you’ll slowly burn you’re your account. 

36
00:02:57,120 --> 00:03:02,280
The reality is that fair value gaps 
are just one piece of the puzzle. 

37
00:03:02,280 --> 00:03:08,080
On their own, they don’t give reliable signals. 
They work with other market signs to give a  

38
00:03:08,080 --> 00:03:12,400
full picture. We’ll talk about this later.
 
Chapter 3: Identifying Fair Value Gaps on Charts

39
00:03:12,400 --> 00:03:16,880
Now let's talk about spotting 
fair value gaps on your charts. 

40
00:03:16,880 --> 00:03:20,240
We're looking at a specific three-candle pattern. 

41
00:03:20,240 --> 00:03:26,520
For a bullish gap, check if the upper shadow of 
the first candle doesn't touch the lower shadow  

42
00:03:26,520 --> 00:03:32,960
of the third candle in the sequence. The 
space between them is your Fair Value Gap. 

43
00:03:32,960 --> 00:03:37,120
For a bearish gap, check if the 
lower shadow of the first candle  

44
00:03:37,120 --> 00:03:44,280
doesn't touch the upper shadow of the third 
candle. This area is your Fair Value Gap.
  

45
00:03:44,280 --> 00:03:50,080
The market makes these gaps when big players 
make aggressive moves. This happens because  

46
00:03:50,080 --> 00:03:56,800
there's not enough trading activity in that price 
zone - creating what we call a liquidity void. 

47
00:03:56,800 --> 00:04:04,000
Think of it like this: A Fair Value Gap shows up 
during a quick price move where one big player  

48
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:10,280
grabs all the available trades. This creates 
a space where almost no trading happened.
  

49
00:04:10,280 --> 00:04:14,360
The trick is to spot when 
these candles don't overlap. 

50
00:04:14,360 --> 00:04:20,240
So in a bullish gap, the high of the first 
candle shouldn't touch the low of the third. 

51
00:04:20,240 --> 00:04:25,360
In a bearish gap, the low of the first 
shouldn't touch the high of the third.
  

52
00:04:25,360 --> 00:04:30,160
When you're looking for these gaps, pay 
attention to the market structure too. 

53
00:04:30,160 --> 00:04:35,200
Bullish gaps often show up at support.
Bearish gaps tend to form after  

54
00:04:35,200 --> 00:04:39,320
a rise to resistance.
Like I said, in theory,  

55
00:04:39,320 --> 00:04:45,000
these gaps show up when big players make 
moves. They can grab all the trades at once,  

56
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:47,960
marking an imbalance on the chart.
 
Chapter 4: Fair Value Gaps and Market Structure

57
00:04:47,960 --> 00:04:52,320
So fair value gaps are closely 
tied to market structure. 

58
00:04:52,320 --> 00:04:55,960
They often form at key points 
in the market's movement,  

59
00:04:55,960 --> 00:05:03,040
giving us clues about where price might go next.
In a bullish market structure, fair value gaps  

60
00:05:03,040 --> 00:05:09,480
typically form during strong upward moves.
The gap shows where buyers were so eager,  

61
00:05:09,480 --> 00:05:15,080
that they skipped over some price levels.
This can be a sign that the upward trend is  

62
00:05:15,080 --> 00:05:18,200
strong and likely to continue.
 
In a bearish market structure,  

63
00:05:18,200 --> 00:05:25,680
fair value gaps form during sharp downward moves.
Here, sellers are pushing the price down so fast,  

64
00:05:25,680 --> 00:05:30,040
that some levels get skipped.
This can indicate that the bearish  

65
00:05:30,040 --> 00:05:35,080
trend has strength behind it.
 
Fair value gaps can also mark  

66
00:05:35,080 --> 00:05:42,320
potential turning points in the market structure.
If price returns to fill a gap and then reverses,  

67
00:05:42,320 --> 00:05:46,520
it might signal a continuation 
in the existing trend. 
  

68
00:05:46,520 --> 00:05:50,960
When looking at market structure, 
consider different timeframes. 

69
00:05:50,960 --> 00:05:56,960
A fair value gap on a smaller timeframe 
might not be visible on a larger one. 

70
00:05:56,960 --> 00:06:01,800
But it can still affect how 
price moves in the short term.
  

71
00:06:01,800 --> 00:06:06,600
Remember, structure is all about 
support and resistance levels. 

72
00:06:06,600 --> 00:06:13,200
Fair value gaps often act as these levels.
Price tends to respect them, either bouncing  

73
00:06:13,200 --> 00:06:19,320
off or breaking through them with force.
 
In ranging markets, fair value gaps  

74
00:06:19,320 --> 00:06:24,360
can mark the edges of the range.
Price might bounce between these gaps,  

75
00:06:24,360 --> 00:06:29,680
creating a clear structure to work with.
 
But please understand that these gaps  

76
00:06:29,680 --> 00:06:33,080
don't exist in isolation.
They're part of the  

77
00:06:33,080 --> 00:06:39,120
bigger picture of market structure.
They work alongside other elements like trends,  

78
00:06:39,120 --> 00:06:44,640
support and resistance, and market phases.
If you trade them on their own, you have  

79
00:06:44,640 --> 00:06:49,800
small chances to make profits. 
 
So when you're analyzing structure,  

80
00:06:49,800 --> 00:06:55,880
look for patterns of higher highs and 
higher lows in an uptrend, or lower  

81
00:06:55,880 --> 00:07:01,480
highs and lower lows in a downtrend.
Fair value gaps often form during  

82
00:07:01,480 --> 00:07:04,760
the strong moves between these swing points.
 
 
Chapter 5: Time Frames for Fair Value Gap Trading

83
00:07:04,760 --> 00:07:07,680
A quick word on time frames.
There can be hundreds  

84
00:07:07,680 --> 00:07:12,840
of gaps in a single trading day.
And they can appear on various time frames.
  

85
00:07:12,840 --> 00:07:19,600
On shorter time frames, fair value gaps are 
more frequent, but have less significance. 

86
00:07:19,600 --> 00:07:26,360
They can be useful for scalping or day trading, 
when looking for quick entries and exits. 

87
00:07:26,360 --> 00:07:31,880
But these gaps might get filled quickly, 
so you need to be fast to act on them.
  

88
00:07:31,880 --> 00:07:37,560
Longer time frames, like 4 
hour or daily, show fewer gaps. 

89
00:07:37,560 --> 00:07:41,400
But when they do appear, 
they often have more impact. 

90
00:07:41,400 --> 00:07:46,240
These gaps can influence price 
movements for several days. 
  

91
00:07:46,240 --> 00:07:52,920
I personally like to use a multiple time frame 
analysis when working with fair value gaps. 

92
00:07:52,920 --> 00:07:58,680
For instance, you might spot a gap on 
a higher time frame, mark the zone,  

93
00:07:58,680 --> 00:08:05,160
but then zoom in to a lower time frame 
to fine-tune their entry or exit points.
  

94
00:08:05,160 --> 00:08:08,640
Remember, price is fractal. Patterns that appear  

95
00:08:08,640 --> 00:08:14,840
on monthly charts can also be seen 
on daily or even 5-minute charts. 

96
00:08:14,840 --> 00:08:18,907
This principle applies to 
fair value gaps as well.
  

97
00:08:18,907 --> 00:08:18,960
Chapter 6: Entry Strategies 
for Fair Value Gap Trades

98
00:08:18,960 --> 00:08:24,080
When trading fair value gaps, timing 
your entry is makes the difference. 

99
00:08:24,080 --> 00:08:29,640
The plan is wait for price to come back 
to the gap before entering your trade. 

100
00:08:29,640 --> 00:08:33,720
This strategy works well because 
these gaps are pulling price back  

101
00:08:33,720 --> 00:08:39,560
to areas where little trading occurred.
Think of this gap as a vacuum in the  

102
00:08:39,560 --> 00:08:44,440
market that needs to be filled.
 
From a supply and demand view,  

103
00:08:44,440 --> 00:08:47,400
here's what happens.
First, a big market  

104
00:08:47,400 --> 00:08:52,920
player enters with massive orders.
They hit the market so hard and fast  

105
00:08:52,920 --> 00:08:58,920
that price jumps, creating that gap. 
 
During this jump, regular traders can't  

106
00:08:58,920 --> 00:09:04,840
keep up with the speed, leaving an area 
where trading activity is super thin. 

107
00:09:04,840 --> 00:09:12,240
When the gap forms, it creates an imbalance.
On one side, you have lots of orders filled,  

108
00:09:12,240 --> 00:09:16,440
but on the other side, there's 
barely any trading activity. 

109
00:09:16,440 --> 00:09:22,280
This imbalance creates a "zone of 
interest" that big players watch closely.
  

110
00:09:22,280 --> 00:09:27,040
So the smart move is waiting 
for price to return to this gap. 

111
00:09:27,040 --> 00:09:32,280
That’s because market makers must 
find fair value for their positions. 

112
00:09:32,280 --> 00:09:38,640
They use these gaps as reference points.
And when price returns to fill the gap, it's often  

113
00:09:38,640 --> 00:09:44,440
because market makers are balancing their books.
 
You'll notice something interesting when price  

114
00:09:44,440 --> 00:09:50,960
comes back to these gaps - it's trying to 
restore balance between buyers and sellers. 

115
00:09:50,960 --> 00:09:56,360
This balancing act happens from 3 reasons.
First, market makers need to fill their  

116
00:09:56,360 --> 00:10:02,800
unfilled orders from the original move.
Also, other traders spot the imbalance  

117
00:10:02,800 --> 00:10:07,040
and try to profit from it.
And finally, the market naturally  

118
00:10:07,040 --> 00:10:12,960
seeks equilibrium at these levels.
 
The key to trading these returns lies  

119
00:10:12,960 --> 00:10:17,200
in understanding the original 
move that created the gap. 

120
00:10:17,200 --> 00:10:22,640
If it was a strong upward move, (a bullish 
displacement), the gap below becomes a  

121
00:10:22,640 --> 00:10:29,440
potential buy zone when price returns. 
The opposite is true for downward moves.
  

122
00:10:29,440 --> 00:10:35,960
Think about the mechanics: When that initial big 
player moved the market so fast, they left behind  

123
00:10:35,960 --> 00:10:41,920
other traders who missed their chance to enter.
When price returns to the gap,  

124
00:10:41,920 --> 00:10:47,720
these traders often jump in, adding to 
the trading activity at these levels.
  

125
00:10:47,720 --> 00:10:54,160
So from a pure supply and demand perspective, the 
fair value gap represents a level where demand  

126
00:10:54,160 --> 00:11:02,080
suddenly overwhelmed supply, in an upward gap, 
or supply overwhelmed demand, in a downward gap. 

127
00:11:02,080 --> 00:11:06,680
The market needs to test these levels 
again to confirm if that imbalance was  

128
00:11:06,680 --> 00:11:12,720
temporary or part of a larger trend.
 
The return to this area often shows  

129
00:11:12,720 --> 00:11:17,160
clear price action signals.
You might see price slow down  

130
00:11:17,160 --> 00:11:23,840
as it approaches the gap, or notice smaller 
timeframe consolidation patterns forming. 
  

131
00:11:23,840 --> 00:11:27,560
Watch how price behaves when 
it returns to fill the gap. 

132
00:11:27,560 --> 00:11:31,960
Clean, swift moves through the gap 
might indicate that more movement in  

133
00:11:31,960 --> 00:11:37,960
that direction is coming. Choppy, slow price 
action might suggest that the level is being  

134
00:11:37,960 --> 00:11:45,400
heavily contested between buyers and sellers.
 
So for a bullish setup, wait for price to return  

135
00:11:45,400 --> 00:11:51,280
to the lower edge of the gap. If price 
bounces off this level, it could signal  

136
00:11:51,280 --> 00:11:56,480
a good entry point for a long trade.
For a bearish setup, watch for price  

137
00:11:56,480 --> 00:12:02,080
to come back to the upper edge of the gap. 
If it struggles to break above this level,  

138
00:12:02,080 --> 00:12:08,560
it might be a good spot to enter a short trade.
 
While waiting for price to return to the gap,  

139
00:12:08,560 --> 00:12:14,480
look for specific candlestick patterns to 
fine-tune your entry. These patterns can give  

140
00:12:14,480 --> 00:12:21,200
you extra confirmation before you enter a trade.
For instance, if you see a bullish engulfing  

141
00:12:21,200 --> 00:12:28,240
pattern form at the lower edge of a fair value 
gap, it could signal a strong buying pressure. 

142
00:12:28,240 --> 00:12:34,720
This might be a good time to enter a long trade. 
 
A long wick at the upper edge of a bearish gap  

143
00:12:34,720 --> 00:12:39,932
could indicate selling pressure, 
implying a potential short entry.
  

144
00:12:39,932 --> 00:12:43,000
FVGs with Break of Structure
Fair value gaps with a Break of Structure  

145
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:49,360
create powerful trade setups, because they combine 
two major elements that show us exactly where  

146
00:12:49,360 --> 00:12:54,480
big players are active in the market.
A break in market structure happens  

147
00:12:54,480 --> 00:13:00,560
when price runs through previous swing 
highs or lows with force. But this break  

148
00:13:00,560 --> 00:13:06,880
needs an gap inside it to count as valid. 
 
Picture the market moving up in a series of  

149
00:13:06,880 --> 00:13:11,800
higher highs and higher lows.
Then suddenly, price drops  

150
00:13:11,800 --> 00:13:17,120
hard through a previous swing low.
During this drop, if we see a gap where  

151
00:13:17,120 --> 00:13:24,760
the candle wicks don't overlap, that's our gap.
Big players pushed price down with real force. 

152
00:13:24,760 --> 00:13:29,560
This area become a magnet 
that pull price back later.
 

153
00:13:29,560 --> 00:13:30,960
Another example. 

154
00:13:30,960 --> 00:13:37,480
You see price moving up, making higher highs.
Then a large player hits the market hard,  

155
00:13:37,480 --> 00:13:42,200
breaking below a key swing low.
During this break, three candles  

156
00:13:42,200 --> 00:13:50,160
form - the middle one creates a gap. This gap 
implies the break in structure might be real.
  

157
00:13:50,160 --> 00:13:54,040
This combination work well 
because it shows 2 things. 

158
00:13:54,040 --> 00:13:57,880
The market structure break 
tells us the trend is changing. 

159
00:13:57,880 --> 00:14:02,920
And the gap shows us exactly where 
big players left their footprint. 

160
00:14:02,920 --> 00:14:08,000
The presence of both signals means 
more than just a random price move. 

161
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:12,280
It shows intentional, 
institutional trading activity. 

162
00:14:12,280 --> 00:14:19,400
When price returns to these levels later, it 
often finds strong support or resistance.
  

163
00:14:19,400 --> 00:14:24,800
What makes this setup special is the 
"vacuum effect" created by the gap. 

164
00:14:24,800 --> 00:14:31,520
Remember that during the fast move that broke 
market structure, some orders didn't get filled. 

165
00:14:31,520 --> 00:14:37,440
This creates an area where price 
needs to return to find "fair value".
  

166
00:14:37,440 --> 00:14:42,400
You'll notice these setups work 
best when 3 condition are met: 

167
00:14:42,400 --> 00:14:46,080
First, when the break in 
structure is clean and strong, 

168
00:14:46,080 --> 00:14:50,760
The fair value gap forms right at 
the point where structure breaks. 

169
00:14:50,760 --> 00:14:55,800
And third, price moves away 
quickly after creating the gap. 

170
00:14:55,800 --> 00:15:00,560
So when market makers move price fast 
enough to break structure and leave  

171
00:15:00,560 --> 00:15:05,360
a gap, they're showing their hand.
They're telling us they have strong  

172
00:15:05,360 --> 00:15:10,000
interest at these levels.
 
The same for a buy signal. 

173
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:16,760
Look for a clear break of previous swing highs.
Check for a gap forming during this break. 

174
00:15:16,760 --> 00:15:20,920
Then wait for price to return 
to the fair value gap level. 

175
00:15:20,920 --> 00:15:27,760
And watch how price reacts when it hits the zone.
 
The setup becomes even stronger when the gap  

176
00:15:27,760 --> 00:15:34,800
coincides with the actual break point in market 
structure. This creates a "double reference" point  

177
00:15:34,800 --> 00:15:41,240
that market makers use to balance their books.
The liquidity void that comes with the fair value  

178
00:15:41,240 --> 00:15:46,920
gap adds another layer of confirmation.
It shows that one side of the market was  

179
00:15:46,920 --> 00:15:52,680
completely overwhelmed during the move.
This imbalance needs to be corrected,  

180
00:15:52,680 --> 00:15:59,840
which is why price often returns to these levels.
 
So after spotting the break in structure and gap,  

181
00:15:59,840 --> 00:16:04,280
don't chase the initial move.
The best trades come when price revisits  

182
00:16:04,280 --> 00:16:10,120
these levels and shows clear reaction.
This gap becomes a key reference level  

183
00:16:10,120 --> 00:16:13,040
for the new trend direction.
 
FVGs with supply/demand zones

184
00:16:13,040 --> 00:16:18,600
Supply and demand zones mark the spots 
where smart money builds positions. 

185
00:16:18,600 --> 00:16:23,160
Think of them as launching 
pads where big trades start. 

186
00:16:23,160 --> 00:16:27,720
When you find a fair value gap near 
these zones, you've spotted a place  

187
00:16:27,720 --> 00:16:33,920
where institutional traders showed their 
hand twice - first building positions,  

188
00:16:33,920 --> 00:16:39,760
then moving price fast enough to leave a gap.
 
The strategy works through a simple market  

189
00:16:39,760 --> 00:16:46,880
truth - price wants to trade where it hasn't 
traded before. And those gaps represent prices  

190
00:16:46,880 --> 00:16:51,320
where little to no trading happened.
Again, markets need to fill these  

191
00:16:51,320 --> 00:16:57,560
gaps to find fair value. That's why 
price often returns to these levels.
  

192
00:16:57,560 --> 00:17:03,120
Watch how this plays out on charts. 
First, you'll see price moving normally. 

193
00:17:03,120 --> 00:17:07,360
Then suddenly, a large candle 
appears with no overlap to  

194
00:17:07,360 --> 00:17:11,160
nearby candles - that's your gap.
This tells you someone big just  

195
00:17:11,160 --> 00:17:17,640
moved with purpose. If this happens near a 
supply or demand zone, pay extra attention. 

196
00:17:17,640 --> 00:17:23,200
The process follows clear steps. Price 
builds up in a supply or demand zone.  

197
00:17:23,200 --> 00:17:30,560
Then it moves explosively, creating the gap. 
This fast move shows institutional conviction. 

198
00:17:30,560 --> 00:17:37,600
Later, price must return to fill this gap. 
 
Another signal. You see here a clean fair  

199
00:17:37,600 --> 00:17:44,400
value gap, where candle shadows don't overlap.
The bigger the gap, the stronger the signal. 

200
00:17:44,400 --> 00:17:49,480
As this gap form near this demand 
zone, you've found a sweet spot. 

201
00:17:49,480 --> 00:17:56,200
Then you wait for price to return to the FVG area.
Watch how it reacts. Strong moves often  

202
00:17:56,200 --> 00:18:01,760
follow once the gap starts filling.
In combination with a supply or demand  

203
00:18:01,760 --> 00:18:08,120
zone, I don’t mind if price completely 
fills the gap, and even moves past it. 

204
00:18:08,120 --> 00:18:13,480
I always wait for it to return to the 
origin point, to the demand zone.
  

205
00:18:13,480 --> 00:18:20,440
The technical reason this works ties to liquidity. 
Gaps mark areas with little trading activity. 

206
00:18:20,440 --> 00:18:25,280
When they sit near supply or demand 
zones, you get two powerful forces  

207
00:18:25,280 --> 00:18:31,440
working together - the need to fill the 
gap and the strength of the original zone. 

208
00:18:31,440 --> 00:18:37,280
Your edge comes from spotting these 
combinations early. Look for clean gaps. 

209
00:18:37,280 --> 00:18:41,240
Check if they formed near 
strong supply/demand zones. 

210
00:18:41,240 --> 00:18:48,240
Also, remember the previous chapter, look if 
this move caused a break in market structure. 

211
00:18:48,240 --> 00:18:53,320
These setups offer clear entry 
points with defined risk.
 
  

212
00:18:53,320 --> 00:18:57,880
This is a clear example of 
how big players move markets. 

213
00:18:57,880 --> 00:19:05,360
They build positions in zones, create gaps with 
fast moves, then let price return to fill them. 

214
00:19:05,360 --> 00:19:09,280
Each step leaves clues on 
charts through price action. 

215
00:19:09,280 --> 00:19:12,800
Price moves this way because 
markets seek liquidity. 

216
00:19:12,800 --> 00:19:17,760
This creates a rhythm you can 
trade – accumulation, expansion,  

217
00:19:17,760 --> 00:19:21,200
gap creation, then gap filling.
 
FVGs in Premium/Discount Zones

218
00:19:21,200 --> 00:19:27,720
Fair Value Gaps in premium or discount zones 
show where smart money plans their moves. 

219
00:19:27,720 --> 00:19:31,280
Market makers work in 
specific ways at these spots. 

220
00:19:31,280 --> 00:19:37,520
In discount zones, they start buying. 
In premium zones, they start selling. 

221
00:19:37,520 --> 00:19:42,880
This creates a rhythm in the market - a 
back and forth movement you can trade.
  

222
00:19:42,880 --> 00:19:47,200
The power of this setup comes 
from market maker behavior. 

223
00:19:47,200 --> 00:19:53,000
They need to do fair valuation for 
both their entry and exit positions. 

224
00:19:53,000 --> 00:19:58,640
This means they look at premium and discount 
zones as places to start big moves.
  

225
00:19:59,400 --> 00:20:05,280
You need to see the bigger picture first. Look 
at the total range of the larger price move. 

226
00:20:05,280 --> 00:20:10,080
Find where price sits compared 
to recent highs and lows. 

227
00:20:10,080 --> 00:20:17,560
Then spot the reference points market makers 
watch - the fair value gaps and liquidity voids. 

228
00:20:17,560 --> 00:20:25,360
The middle ground, called equilibrium, marks 
the 50% point between swing highs and lows. 

229
00:20:25,360 --> 00:20:30,280
This helps you know if price 
sits in premium or discount. 
  

230
00:20:30,280 --> 00:20:34,680
Market mechanics make this 
work. After big market moves,  

231
00:20:34,680 --> 00:20:39,320
most traders chase the trend.
Smart money does the opposite. 

232
00:20:39,320 --> 00:20:45,160
They expect a pullback before the next move.
These pullbacks often happen right at fair  

233
00:20:45,160 --> 00:20:52,280
value gaps in premium or discount areas.
The process shows up clearly on charts.  

234
00:20:52,280 --> 00:20:58,080
Sharp price runs leave behind gaps - 
areas where little trading happened. 

235
00:20:58,080 --> 00:21:04,880
These spots become targets for future trades.
When they sit in premium or discount zones,  

236
00:21:04,880 --> 00:21:10,280
they mark prime trading opportunities.
 
So watch how price behaves in these  

237
00:21:10,280 --> 00:21:16,680
zones. In premium areas with a fair 
value gap, look for selling pressure. 

238
00:21:16,680 --> 00:21:21,360
In discount areas with gaps, 
watch for buying pressure. 

239
00:21:21,360 --> 00:21:26,240
The mix of zone location and the 
gap, creates stronger signals.
  

240
00:21:26,240 --> 00:21:31,560
Remember what we talked before, 
market structure plays a key role too. 

241
00:21:31,560 --> 00:21:38,400
True breaks in structure often leave gaps 
behind. These gaps confirm the break's strength. 

242
00:21:38,400 --> 00:21:44,640
When they form in premium or discount 
zones, they show even more power. 

243
00:21:44,640 --> 00:21:52,040
Again, the best trades come when multiple 
factors line up - zone location, gap presence,  

244
00:21:52,040 --> 00:21:58,520
break in structure and clear price action.
Market makers use these areas to build positions.  

245
00:21:59,560 --> 00:22:04,560
They accumulate in discount zones 
and distribute in premium zones. 

246
00:22:04,560 --> 00:22:10,800
And finding gaps at these spots shows 
you where they plan to move price next.
  

247
00:22:10,800 --> 00:22:17,000
The strategy works because it follows market 
maker goals. They need to find fair value for  

248
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:23,080
positions. Premium and discount zones 
mark places where they take action. 

249
00:22:23,080 --> 00:22:28,600
Fair value gaps in these zones show 
exactly where they moved with force. 

250
00:22:28,600 --> 00:22:33,960
Best trades develop this way. Price 
reaches a premium or discount zone. 

251
00:22:33,960 --> 00:22:39,160
You find an FVG nearby. Then 
price shows reversal signs. 

252
00:22:39,160 --> 00:22:46,520
The whole process repeats in cycles. Price 
moves between fair value, premium, and discount. 

253
00:22:46,520 --> 00:22:50,080
And each cycle leaves gaps behind. 
 
FVGs - Fibonacci confluence

254
00:22:50,080 --> 00:22:56,400
Fibonacci levels match natural market moves, 
and when they line up with Fair Value Gaps,  

255
00:22:56,400 --> 00:23:01,560
they create strong trade opportunities.
Think of it like using two different  

256
00:23:01,560 --> 00:23:08,000
tools that point to the same spot - 
it makes that spot much more special. 

257
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:13,280
The magic happens because different 
types of traders watch different things. 

258
00:23:13,280 --> 00:23:20,120
Some traders only trade fair value 
gaps, while others only use Fibonacci. 

259
00:23:20,120 --> 00:23:25,760
When these levels match up, both groups 
of traders see a good trade opportunity. 

260
00:23:25,760 --> 00:23:31,160
This creates more buying or selling 
pressure at that exact spot.
  

261
00:23:31,160 --> 00:23:39,240
The golden zone between the 50% and 61% 
Fibonacci levels attracts smart money attention. 

262
00:23:39,240 --> 00:23:45,400
When a gap sits in this area, you've found 
a place where two powerful forces meet. 

263
00:23:45,400 --> 00:23:49,280
This double confirmation 
makes your trades stronger.
  

264
00:23:49,280 --> 00:23:56,000
In an uptrend, look for gaps that line up with 
Fibonacci levels for buying opportunities. 

265
00:23:56,000 --> 00:24:02,080
In a downtrend, search for gaps matching 
Fibonacci levels for selling chances. 

266
00:24:02,080 --> 00:24:09,800
Think about how markets move. After a strong 
push, price pulls back to test previous levels. 

267
00:24:09,800 --> 00:24:14,560
Smart traders use Fibonacci to 
find these pullback targets. 

268
00:24:14,560 --> 00:24:21,720
When these levels match a fair value gap, they 
show where big players plan their next moves.
  

269
00:24:21,720 --> 00:24:25,120
The process starts with 
finding the right swing points. 

270
00:24:25,120 --> 00:24:31,480
Draw your Fibonacci from the highest high to 
the lowest low in the recent price action. 

271
00:24:31,480 --> 00:24:38,680
This gives you the framework for finding the sweet 
spots where a fair value gap might matter most. 

272
00:24:38,680 --> 00:24:45,320
A lot of big traders watch these same levels. 
Some use Fibonacci to plan their trades,  

273
00:24:45,320 --> 00:24:50,040
looking for spots where they 
can build or exit positions. 

274
00:24:50,040 --> 00:24:56,120
And when you see a fair value gap at these 
levels, you might want to take action.
  

275
00:24:56,120 --> 00:25:00,920
The real power comes from understanding 
what these confluences mean. 

276
00:25:00,920 --> 00:25:06,000
Fibonacci levels themselves don't 
act as support or resistance. 

277
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:10,040
Instead, they help you find 
liquidity blocks - places  

278
00:25:10,040 --> 00:25:17,600
where fair value gaps show market imbalances.
Then watch how price reacts at these spots. 

279
00:25:17,600 --> 00:25:23,160
A strong gap needs a big, clean 
separation between candle shadows. 

280
00:25:23,160 --> 00:25:29,720
When this gap lines up with key Fibonacci 
levels, especially the 50 and 61% zone,  

281
00:25:29,720 --> 00:25:35,240
you've found a high-probability setup.
 
The strategy works because it combines  

282
00:25:35,240 --> 00:25:40,400
two types of market psychology.
Fibonacci shows natural pullback  

283
00:25:40,400 --> 00:25:46,560
points where traders expect reactions.
Fair value gaps show where big money  

284
00:25:46,560 --> 00:25:53,440
moved fast enough to leave traces.
And together, they create stronger signals.
  

285
00:25:53,440 --> 00:26:00,600
Remember that trends make this work better. In a 
strong uptrend, gaps that line up with Fibonacci  

286
00:26:00,600 --> 00:26:06,280
levels make great buying zones.
The opposite works in downtrends. 

287
00:26:06,280 --> 00:26:12,520
The trend gives you another layer of 
confluence, making your trades even stronger.
  

288
00:26:12,520 --> 00:26:18,800
The plan is simple. Wait for price to reach 
the Fibonacci level, where your gap sits. 

289
00:26:18,800 --> 00:26:23,760
Look for signs that price respects 
both the level and the gap. 

290
00:26:23,760 --> 00:26:28,840
The best trades come when price pierces 
the confluence zone, and rejects it with  

291
00:26:28,840 --> 00:26:36,840
a strong candlestick signal. I look mainly for 
candles with large wicks, or engulfing patterns. 

292
00:26:36,840 --> 00:26:42,240
Time frames matter too. While this 
strategy works on any chart, I often  

293
00:26:42,240 --> 00:26:48,360
watch the 4-hour and the hourly charts.
These longer views help you spot the  

294
00:26:48,360 --> 00:26:53,280
strongest confluences between 
Fibonacci and fair value gaps.
  

295
00:26:53,280 --> 00:26:58,920
Again, the technical reason this works 
ties to liquidity. Big players need  

296
00:26:58,920 --> 00:27:04,920
certain price levels to build positions. 
They use Fibonacci to find these spots. 

297
00:27:04,920 --> 00:27:10,720
When they move fast enough to create gaps 
at these levels, they show their hand twice. 

298
00:27:10,720 --> 00:27:15,360
Trading becomes simpler with this 
approach. You don't chase price. 

299
00:27:15,360 --> 00:27:22,960
Instead, you wait for it to reach these special 
spots where Fibonacci and fair value gaps meet. 

300
00:27:22,960 --> 00:27:27,680
This patience puts you in position 
for high-probability moves. 

301
00:27:27,680 --> 00:27:34,560
The whole process flows naturally. Markets 
move up or down with force, creating gaps. 

302
00:27:34,560 --> 00:27:40,240
Price pulls back to Fibonacci levels. 
When these align, you find spots where  

303
00:27:40,240 --> 00:27:45,280
smart money are likely to act.
 
 
Think of confluence like different  

304
00:27:45,280 --> 00:27:52,520
layers. Each layer, like the gap, Fibonacci, 
trend direction, the candlestick confirmation,  

305
00:27:52,520 --> 00:27:57,840
makes your trade setup stronger.
The more layers of confluence you have, the  

306
00:27:57,840 --> 00:28:05,800
higher the probability of your trade working out.
And use these confluence zones as areas, not exact  

307
00:28:05,800 --> 00:28:14,000
prices. Markets rarely turn exactly at a specific 
price. Instead, they often react within a zone. 

308
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:20,440
So give your trades room to breathe by 
thinking in zones, rather than exact prices!
  

309
00:28:20,440 --> 00:28:25,920
I prefer this approach because it also 
helps you avoid many fake breakouts. 

310
00:28:25,920 --> 00:28:32,440
Instead of chasing price, you're waiting for 
it to return to these high-probability zones. 

311
00:28:32,440 --> 00:28:39,760
This patient approach will keep you out of those 
common breakout traps that catch many traders. 

312
00:28:39,760 --> 00:28:43,040
Now, if you want to learn 
other smart money tactics,  

313
00:28:43,040 --> 00:28:53,200
you need to watch one of these videos next.

